The Center for Court Innovation is a non-profit organization that works to create a more effective and humane justice system by performing original research and helping launch reforms by guiding justice innovators, nationally and internationally. The Center creates operating projects that have been documented to reduce the use of jail and prison, assist victims of crime, and strengthen communities.
The Center's Data Analytics and Applied Research (DAAR) team is seeking a Data Analyst to work primarily on the Supervised Release Program (SRP), a pretrial alternative to bail and detention in New York City. Reporting to the Senior Data Analyst, the Data Analyst will provide critical data support to this innovative, cross-borough initiative by assisting with regular data quality audits, database management tasks, recurring external reporting, developing comprehensive data documentation and training materials. The Data Analyst will also collaborate with researchers to generate analyses, internal reports, visualizations, and interactive dashboards that help monitor and evaluate program indicators and outcomes.
This position offers an opportunity to develop and implement data processes and protocols that ensure criminal justice researchers, stakeholders and policymakers are equipped with the valid and reliable data needed to identify trends, measure outcomes, and inform policy.
Responsibilities include but are not limited to:
Conduct regular data audits by generating automated reports that effectively and efficiently flag data discrepancies that need to be addressed in the Center’s case management database;
Assist in analyzing data for common trends in data quality and systematize findings to identify and prioritize specific areas for improvement;
Review modifications to the database, assisting with database testing, to ensure standardization across multiple SRP sites;
Support the management of the organization-wide database more generally (e.g., gather, analyze, and determine data and information needs across multiple initiatives and propose solutions to streamline data collection and reporting practices);
Assist in developing and maintaining data codebooks and database documentation;
Provide technical support to the DAAR team:
Build and maintain interactive dashboards and produce data visualizations using Tableau;
Prepare analytical datasets by querying, extracting, merging, cleaning, and re-coding both programmatic data from the Center’s case management database, and data from official NYS Courts and other external data sources;
Perform quality assurance checks on queries and data reports;
Contribute to/assist with data analyses for special research projects;
Collaborate with the Center’s Technology team to improve DAAR-Tech processes:
With Senior Data Analyst, act as DAAR liaison with Data Engineer on development of data warehouse and various data pipelines, assisting with set-up and troubleshooting of automated reporting processes;
Work closely with team management and the technology department in our upcoming transition from a legacy case management system (proprietary Oracle database) to Salesforce;
Additional relevant tasks, as needed.
Qualifications: The ideal candidate will have a Master’s Degree or a Bachelor’s Degree in a quantitative discipline, plus 1-2 years’ of relevant data experience, preferably in the criminal justice field. The successful candidate must bring a passion for improving the criminal justice system along with extensive knowledge of relational databases, data visualization software (Tableau), and a demonstrated ability to write complex queries in SQL (or other programming languages used to extract and manipulate data). Qualified applicants must be inherent problem solvers with exceptional attention to detail, strong logical reasoning, analytical, and communication (written and oral) skills. Other qualifications include:
Working knowledge of RDBMS concepts (relational databases), experience with database interface and query software, such as Toad, Microsoft SQL Server Management Studio, or Oracle SQL Developer, and a demonstrated ability to write complex SQL queries (or equivalency) to extract and manipulate data are required;
Familiarity with Salesforce platforms is preferred;
Statistical software syntax expertise is preferred (R, Python, SPSS, SAS, Stata, etc.);
Professional experience using data visualization software and/or mapping tools such as ESRI ArcGIS, QGIS or equivalency in a professional setting is preferred (Tableau skills strongly preferred);
Proficiency in Excel (pivot tables, filters, basic formulas) is required; Access, PowerPoint (or Prezi) skills also preferred;
Experience manipulating and analyzing large datasets is required; familiarity with administrative and government datasets is a plus;
Strong task management skills and a demonstrated ability to meet deliverables in a timely manner are required;
Demonstrated ability to work independently and take initiative to solve problems as they arise is a must; Applicants must also be comfortable collaborating with teammates as well as colleagues from various other departments, including technology and operations.
Location: Midtown, NY; temporarily remote.
Compensation: Salary range starts at $71,500 and is commensurate with experience. Excellent benefits package including comprehensive health, dental and life insurance, four weeks paid vacation, paid sick time, WageWorks, Flexible Spending Account plans for health and dependent care, a 403(b) retirement plan and a 401(k) retirement plan with a generous employer match.
The Fund for the City of New York/Center for Court Innovation is an equal opportunity employer. The Center does not discriminate on the basis of race, color, religion, gender identity, gender expression, pregnancy, national origin, age, military service eligibility, veteran status, sexual orientation, marital status, disability, or any other category protected by law. We strongly encourage and seek applications from women, people of color, members of the lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender communities as well as individuals with prior contact with the criminal justice system.
As of September 9, 2021, all new hires are required to be vaccinated against the COVID-19 virus, unless they have been granted a reasonable accommodation for medical, disability or religious reasons by the Center’s Human Resources Department.
In compliance with federal law, all persons hired will be required to verify identity and eligibility to work in the United States and to complete an employment eligibility verification document form upon hire. Only applicants under consideration will be contacted. No phone calls please.
